<DOC><DOCNO> AP890918-0180 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-18-89 1058EDT</FILEID><FIRST>a a BC-History Adv25   09-18 0582</FIRST><SECOND>BC-History, Adv25,0605</SECOND><HEAD>$adv25</HEAD><HEAD>For Release Monday, Sept. 25</HEAD><HEAD>Today In History</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Today is Monday, September 25, the 268th day of 1989. There are97 days left in the year.   Today's highlight in history:   Two hundred years ago, on September 25, 1789, the first U.S.Congress, meeting in New York, adopted 12 amendments to theConstitution and sent them to the states for ratification. Ten ofthe amendments became the Bill of Rights.   On this date:   In 1513, Spanish explorer Vasco Nunez de Balboa crossed theIsthmus of Panama and discovered the Pacific Ocean.   In 1690, ``Publick Occurrences,'' the first American newspaper,published its first and last edition in Boston.   In 1775, American Revolutionary War hero Ethan Allen was capturedby the British as he led an attack on Montreal.   In 1890, Mormon Church president Wilford Woodruff issued amanifesto formally renouncing polygamy.   In 1890, Congress established Yosemite National Park.   In 1904, a New York City police officer ordered a woman namedLillian Orr, who was riding in an automobile on Fifth Avenue, tostop smoking a cigarette, in accordance with an unwritten ruleagainst women smoking in public.   In 1919, President Wilson became seriously ill and collapsedafter a speech in Pueblo, Colo., during a national speaking tour insupport of the Treaty of Versailles.   In 1957, with 300 Army troops standing guard, nine black childrenwho had been forced to withdraw from Central High School in LittleRock, Ark., because of unruly crowds were escorted to their classes.   In 1962, Sonny Liston knocked out Floyd Patterson in round one towin the world heavyweight title at Comiskey Park in Chicago.   In 1964, the situation comedy ``Gomer Pyle, USMC'' made its debuton CBS-TV.   In 1973, the three-man crew of the U.S. space laboratory Skylab 2made a safe splashdown in the Pacific after spending 59 days inorbit.   In 1978, 144 people were killed when a Pacific Southwest AirlinesBoeing 727 and a Cessna private plane collided in the air over SanDiego, Calif., and crashed.   In 1981, Sandra Day O'Connor was sworn in as the first womanjustice on the U.S. Supreme Court.   Ten years ago: Addressing the UN General Assembly, Soviet ForeignMinister Andrei A. Gromyko said ``falsehoods'' were being aimed athis country and Cuba _ an apparent reference to U.S. charges ofSoviet combat troops in Cuba. The military government of Argentinaexpelled publisher Jacobo Timerman. The musical ``Evita,'' based onthe life of Eva Peron, opened on Broadway.   Five years ago: One day after President Reagan addressed the UNGeneral Assembly, the official Soviet news agency Tass rejected theAmerican leader's assurances of a U.S. desire for arms cuts as``absolutely groundless.''   One year ago: Republican George Bush amd Democrat Michael Dukakisclashed over deficits, drugs and the Pledge of Allegiance in theirfirst presidential debate. Former ``first brother'' Billy Carterdied in Plains, Ga., at age 51. Florence Griffith Joyner won thewomen's 100-meter dash at the Seoul Olympics.   Today's Birthdays: New York Yankee broadcaster Phil Rizzuto is71. ABC news correspondent Barbara Walters is 58. Dancer-actressJuliet Prowse is 53. Actor Robert Walden is 46. Actor-producerMichael Douglas is 45. Actor Mark Hamill is 37. Actor ChristopherReeve is 37. Actress Heather Locklear is 28.   Thought for Today: ``The Constitution belongs to the people andnot the people to the Constitution.'' _ Theodore Roosevelt, 26thpresident of the United States (1858-1919).</TEXT><NOTE>End Advance for Use Monday, September 25</NOTE></DOC>